    "body": "I really really miss the resizer!!!\n\nChanging the figsize is NOT an alternative to the resize handle. \n\n``` python\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,10))\nax.plot(range(10))\nplt.show()\n\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,5))\nax.plot(range(10))\nplt.show()\n```\n\nThe font size and line widths are the same, but the plot is twice as big. When I'm trying to make publication ready figures, it is nice so set the figsize that will put the text in proportion with the plot, and use the resize handle to get a closer look.\n\nIs there another solution to quickly and easily scale figures? Like actually scale everything? Or do I have to output to a file and view it from there now?\n"
